items.synopsis: Polls are beginning to close across the country and counting is underway in the Voice to Parliament referendum. Follow our live blog for the latest updates.

title.children: NSW and Tasmania vote No, other states too early to call as counting starts in Voice referendum

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The ABC projects that a majority of voters in New South Wales have rejected the proposal to enshrine an Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Voice in the constitution. It is clear that at least two states have voted No. If a third state votes against the proposed constitutional amendment, the referendum will have been defeated. So far, no states have voted Yes, with four still in doubt.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ABC projection: New South Wales has voted No on the Voice referendum

children.content: The ABC projects that a majority of voters in New South Wales have rejected the proposal to enshrine an Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Voice in the constitution.
It is clear that at least two states have voted No.
If a third state votes against the proposed constitutional amendment, the referendum will have been defeated.
So far, no states have voted Yes, with four still in doubt.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It's officially 6pm in Queensland, so polling has now closed. Polling will soon close in the Northern Territory, and then later on in Western Australia. If you're just joining us: The ABC projects that Tasmania has voted No on the Voice. The ABC projects that the Australian Capital Territory has voted in favour of enshrining a Voice in the constitution.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The ABC projects that the Australian Capital Territory has voted in favour of enshrining a Voice in the constitution. With 2.6 per cent of the vote counted, Yes has a clear majority in all ACT electorates. Votes in the ACT are counted in the national total, but territories are not included in the requirement for passing that a majority of voters in a majority of states vote in favour.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ABC projection: The ACT has voted in favour of a Voice

children.content: The ABC projects that the Australian Capital Territory has voted in favour of enshrining a Voice in the constitution.

Votes in the ACT are counted in the national total, but territories are not included in the requirement for passing that a majority of voters in a majority of states vote in favour.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Australia will provide an initial $10 million in humanitarian assistance for civilians affected by the conflict in Gaza. That will be split between $3 million through the International Committee of the Red Cross to fund "urgent needs like restoring essential services and providing medical support to victims of the conflict" and $7 million through United Nations agencies providing critical aid. The UN support will include emergency water supplies, nutrition, sanitation and hygiene services and child protection. The Gaza Strip has been cut off from food, water and fuel supplies coming through Israel, with electricity also cut and several health facilities damaged in air strikes. "We have seen devastating loss of innocent life since the heinous attacks on Israel by brutal terrorist group Hamas," Foreign Minister Penny Wong said. "Far from representing the Palestinian people, Hamas undermines Palestinian needs and aspirations. "We continue to call for the unconditional release of all hostages. We stand with Israel and reiterate its right to defend itself. "President Biden has called on Israel to operate by the rules of war in its response to Hamas attacks — we join him and others in that call. "We call for safe and unimpeded humanitarian access to civilians affected by the worsening humanitarian crisis in Gaza. "We call for the establishment of a corridor to enable humanitarian needs to be met. And we support the work of the United States, Egypt and others towards this goal. "Adherence to international humanitarian law must be prioritised — including the protection of civilians, wherever they live."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australia announces $10 million in aid for civilians in Gaza

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Israeli Army arabic language spokesman Avichay Adraee has posted on X, formerly Twitter, that residents of Gaza City will be allowed to leave on two roads between 10am and 4pm local time. It's currently just before 9am in Gaza. The post on X, which includes a map, translated from Arabic into English reads: An important statement to the residents of Gaza City  In recent days, we have appealed to you to leave Gaza City to the south of Wadi Gaza in order to preserve your safety. I would like to inform you that the IDF will allow movement on the indicated streets without any harm between the hours of 10:00-16:00. For your safety, take advantage of the short time to move south — from Beit Hanoun to Khan Yunis. If you care about yourself and your loved ones, go south as instructed. Rest assured that Hamas leaders have taken care of themselves and are taking cover from strikes in the region. Residents of Al-Shati, Rimal, and west of Zeitoun will also be allowed to move on Daldul and Al-Seena Streets towards Salah Al-Deen and Al-Bahr Streets. Note: The translation of this tweet has been updated to correct several town names.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Israeli Army will allow safe movement out of Gaza City for six hours

It's currently just before 9am in Gaza.
The post on X, which includes a map, translated from Arabic into English reads:

An important statement to the residents of Gaza City  In recent days, we have appealed to you to leave Gaza City to the south of Wadi Gaza in order to preserve your safety. I would like to inform you that the IDF will allow movement on the indicated streets without any harm between the hours of 10:00-16:00. For your safety, take advantage of the short time to move south — from Beit Hanoun to Khan Yunis. If you care about yourself and your loved ones, go south as instructed. Rest assured that Hamas leaders have taken care of themselves and are taking cover from strikes in the region. Residents of Al-Shati, Rimal, and west of Zeitoun will also be allowed to move on Daldul and Al-Seena Streets towards Salah Al-Deen and Al-Bahr Streets.
Note: The translation of this tweet has been updated to correct several town names.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israel Defense Force spokesperson Jonathan Conricus said in the live stream there were Israeli Reserve soldiers around the Gaza Strip awaiting information for the next stage of the operation. Mr Conricus has reaffirmed the IDF's objective was to target Hamas. "The end state of this war is that we will dismantle Hamas and their military capabilities and fundamentally change the situation so that Hamas never again has the ability to inflict any damage on Israeli civilians or soldiers," he said. He said in the broadcast that "Palestinian civilians in Gaza are not our enemies." "If they were, the situation in Gaza would be entirely different," he said. "We are trying to do the right thing, we are trying to evacuate civilians in order to minimise the risk for them."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: The IDF releases situational update

children.content: Israel Defense Force spokesperson Jonathan Conricus said in the live stream there were Israeli Reserve soldiers around the Gaza Strip awaiting information for the next stage of the operation.
Mr Conricus has reaffirmed the IDF's objective was to target Hamas.

"The end state of this war is that we will dismantle Hamas and their military capabilities and fundamentally change the situation so that Hamas never again has the ability to inflict any damage on Israeli civilians or soldiers," he said.
He said in the broadcast that "Palestinian civilians in Gaza are not our enemies."
"If they were, the situation in Gaza would be entirely different," he said.
"We are trying to do the right thing, we are trying to evacuate civilians in order to minimise the risk for them."
